{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Not only was he the prime exponent of a proletarian cultural revolution; it was Bogdanov's ideas which provided justification for concern for the environment.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "And his ideas are not only important to environmentalists because they were associated with this conservation movement; more significantly they are of continuing relevance because they confront the root causes of environmental destruction in the present, and offer what is perhaps the only way to overcome these causes.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Bogdanov claimed that it was only with Marx's publication of A Contribution to the Critique of Political Economy in 1859 that the foundations were laid for a scientific study of the structure and dynamics of human society.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "However Bogdanov was highly critical of Marxists who treated Marx's works as the embodiment of absolute and eternal truths.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "He equated this with outmoded authoritarian and religious frames of mind.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Bogdanov represented human society as an integral part of nature, an energetic process subject to self-adjusting natural processes which could be scientifically measured, and he formulated in terms of this scheme an interpretation of the historical succession of social systems and a new theory of knowledge.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Bogdanov argued that nature and society together are perpetually changing, although without there being any purpose in this change, and the social sciences should be based on natural science models.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "The key process revealing the regularities of social change is adaptation, the main mechanism of which is the social selection of the most effective techniques for the satisfaction of changing social needs.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Bogdanov turned to the empirio-criticism of Ernst Mach, Ostwald's source of inspiration, and of Richard Avenarius, synthesizing their epistemological views with Marx's theory of social history to formulate an original theory of knowledge which he called empiriomonism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Bogdanov signified by the 'monism' of his 'empiriomonism,' a world-view guided by a single comprehensive principle, which provides a key to all understanding and is applicable to the natural as well as the social sciences, so that reality can be experienced as one unitary organic whole, with all its parts interrelated.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Bogdanov argued that the components of experience are not a priori elements; there are many possible ways to divide experience into elements, some more useful than others.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "He argued that workers who initially develop their separate perspectives through labor, come into conflict, which is intensified by the urge to complete a task.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "The conflict is resolved when one workers' perspective prevails over the other, or some third perspective is generated which is agreed upon.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Bogdanov rejected the claim that any knowledge is absolute, arguing for the relativity of ways of organizing experience to historical conditions.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "He elaborated a philosophy of living experience and a general theory of organization which together reveal the need for and provide the foundation for, a new culture, including a new science.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "He accepted that the full development of his own ideas would only be possible as part of the creation of a classless society; but he also pointed out that the development of these ideas, the creation of a proletarian culture, is a necessary part of creating a classless society.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
